Package nl.pim16aap2.animatedarchitecture.core.structures

Class AbstractStructure

java.lang.Object
nl.pim16aap2.animatedarchitecture.core.structures.AbstractStructure
All Implemented Interfaces:
IStructureConst
Direct Known Subclasses:
BigDoor, Clock, Drawbridge, Flag, GarageDoor, Portcullis, RevolvingDoor, SlidingDoor, Windmill
@ThreadSafe public abstract class AbstractStructure extends Object implements IStructureConst
Represents the abstract base all structure types should extend.

Please read the documentation of nl.pim16aap2.animatedarchitecture.core.structures for more information about the structure system.

Changes made to this class will not automatically be updated in the database. To update the state in the database, you can use either the syncData() method or the syncDataAsync() method.

    • calculateAnimationTime

      protected double calculateAnimationTime(double target)
      Gets the animation time (in seconds) of this structure.

      This basically returns max(target, getMinimumAnimationTime()), logging a message in case the target time is too low.

      Parameters:
      target - The target time.
      Returns:
      The target time if it is bigger than the minimum time, otherwise the minimum.

    • calculateAnimationCycleDistance

      protected abstract double calculateAnimationCycleDistance()
      Calculates the distance traveled per animation by the animated block that travels the furthest.

      For example, for a circular object, this will be a block on the edge, as these blocks travel further per revolution than the blocks closer to the center of the circle.

      This method looks at the distance per animation cycle. The exact definition of a cycle depends on the implementation of the structure. For a big door, for example, a cycle could be a single toggle, or a quarter circle. To keep things easy, a revolving structure (which may not have a definitive end to its animation) could define a cycle as quarter circle as well.

      The distance value is used to calculate getMinimumAnimationTime() and getBaseAnimationTime().

      Returns:
      The longest distance traveled by an animated block measured in blocks.

    • calculateAnimationRange

      protected abstract Rectangle calculateAnimationRange()
      Calculates the rectangle describing the limits within an animation of this door takes place.

      At no point during an animation will any animated block leave this cuboid, though not guarantees are given regarding how tight the cuboid fits around the animated blocks.

      Returns:
      The animation range.

    • getMinimumAnimationTime

      public double getMinimumAnimationTime()
      Gets the lower time limit for an animation.

      Because animated blocks have a speed limit, as determined by IConfig.maxBlockSpeed(), there is also a minimum amount of time for its animation.

      The exact time limit depends on the shape, size, and type of structure.

      Returns:
      The lower animation time limit for this structure in seconds.

    • getBaseAnimationTime

      Returns:
      The base animation time for this structure in seconds.

    • canSkipAnimation

      public boolean canSkipAnimation()
      Checks if this structure can be opened instantly (i.e. skip the animation).

      This describes whether skipping the animation actually does anything. When a structure can skip its animation, it means that the actual toggle has an effect on the world and as such toggling it without an animation does something.

      Structures that do not have any effect other than their animation because all their blocks start and stop at exactly the same place (i.e. flags) cannot skip their animation because skipping the animation would mean removing the blocks of the structure from their locations and then placing them back at exactly the same position. This would be a waste of performance for both the server and the client and as such should be prevented.

      Returns:
      True, if this structure can skip its animation.

    • syncDataAsync

      public final CompletableFuture<DatabaseManager.ActionResult> syncDataAsync()
      Synchronizes this structure and its serialized type-specific data of an AbstractStructure with the database.

      Unlike syncData(), this method will not block the current thread to wait for 1) a read lock to be obtained, 2) the snapshot to be created, and 3) the data to be serialized.
